snippet.textDisplay: Pfff ... most are good, it mostly depends on your peronal preference. That doesn't make them 'better', it's just preference. Also, why aren't there any IBM/Lexmark buckling spring switches in this test? I've had Cherry MX Black, I now have browns (I like the browns a little better). I've had actually good rubber dome keyboards too, like the Microsoft internet keyboard from the late nineties. There's something about the pingyness of the buckling spring switches I like. I started on Atari 8-bit, which had really heavy rubber dome keys, to be able to withstand the violence of people used to typewriters. Honestly, my dad still tries to ram the keyboard through the desk ... he's still typing with arm movements in order to strike the keys with the proper force ... he still owns 2 typewriters too.

snippet.textDisplay: I always enjoyed the click keyboards, probably because I'm old enough to remember when that was all we had. Fortunately, I have my own home office now, so I can close my office door and click away. Just as an added FYI, I have tendinitis, arthritis, and nephropathy in my hands. It sidelined me from working, but you can't keep a computer engineer down. The long travel of my mechanical keyboard causes less stress on my fingers. I'm guessing this is because I'm not bottoming out on a short stroke. In any case, love the review. It's amazing how many choices we have.

snippet.textDisplay:
I've been using a Hybrid Red Dragon Keyboard. So far I haven't missed my old blackwidow.
When it came to the old mechanical; I always had ghosting problems. I do however plan on buying a RD Mechanical sooner or later, I just hope the ghosting issue was just a razer thing. Because writing on it was a pain.

It convinced me for a while that I had a typing problem because of how common double typing was.
Freaked me out big time until I noticed it didn't happen on any other keyboard.
Also fun fact, don't get razer.
I've had two products from them both RMA'd 3 times a piece, until their warranties gave out. (2 years)
Which I'd like to state is not a Me problem as I've had my RD MMO mouse for almost 6 years now, and the Keyboard for about 4.
Not a Single Problem had yet!

snippet.textDisplay:
Bruh, I'm Blues or equivalent. I can't type without my clicketyclack anymore. It's just so satisfying. Of course not something I'd use in an open bureau space for obvious reasons, but for private stuff, writing essays and stuff for university or the usual rapidfire chat typing in videogame chats, etc. they just feel the best.
Can't say I've properly used other types of switches, but when I test-typed different switches in stores, I've never liked the feel of linear switches and the tactile, non-clicky switches just didn't sound nearly as satisfying to use.
I'm also nearly always wearing my headphones and listening music if I'm not gaming so the actual clicky part is very much subdued, though still present in the background.
